Abstract</h2><div id=3D"as0010"><div class=3D"u-margin-s-bottom" id=3D"sp01=
90">We introduce <span><em>physics-informed </em><span><a href=3D"https://w=
ww.sciencedirect.com/topics/chemical-engineering/neural-network" class=3D"t=
opic-link">neural networks</a></span></span><span><span> =E2=80=93 <a href=
=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/physics-and-astronomy/neural-netwo=
rk" class=3D"topic-link">neural networks</a><span> that are trained to solv=
e supervised <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/le=
arning-task" class=3D"topic-link">learning tasks</a> while respecting any g=
iven laws of </span></span><a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/=
physics-and-astronomy/physics" class=3D"topic-link">physics</a><span> descr=
ibed by general nonlinear <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/p=
hysics-and-astronomy/partial-differential-equation" class=3D"topic-link">pa=
rtial differential equations</a><span>. In this work, we present our develo=
pments in the context of solving two main classes of problems: data-driven =
solution and data-driven discovery of <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.=
com/topics/mathematics/partial-differential-equation" class=3D"topic-link">=
partial differential equations</a><span>. Depending on the nature and arran=
gement of the available data, we devise two distinct types of algorithms, n=
amely continuous time and <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/m=
athematics/discrete-time" class=3D"topic-link">discrete time</a> models. Th=
e first type of models forms a new family of </span></span></span></span><e=
m>data-efficient</em><span> spatio-temporal function <a href=3D"https://www=
.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/approximators" class=3D"topic-link">a=
pproximators</a><span>, while the latter type allows the use of arbitrarily=
 accurate implicit Runge=E2=80=93Kutta time stepping schemes with unlimited=
 number of stages. The effectiveness of the proposed framework is demonstra=
ted through a collection of classical problems in fluids, <a href=3D"https:=
//www.sciencedirect.com/topics/physics-and-astronomy/quantum-mechanics" cla=
ss=3D"topic-link">quantum mechanics</a>, reaction=E2=80=93diffusion systems=
, and the propagation of nonlinear shallow-water waves.</span></span></div>=
