iv><section id=3D"se0010"><h2 id=3D"st0040" class=3D"u-h4 u-margin-l-top u-=
margin-xs-bottom">1. Introduction</h2><div class=3D"u-margin-s-bottom" id=
=3D"pr0040"><span>With the explosive growth of available data and computing=
 resources, recent advances in machine learning and <a href=3D"https://www.=
sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/data-analytics" class=3D"topic-link">d=
ata analytics</a><span> have yielded transformative results across diverse =
<a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/scientific-disc=
ipline" class=3D"topic-link">scientific disciplines</a>, including image re=
cognition </span></span><a class=3D"anchor anchor-primary" href=3D"https://=
www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0021999118307125#br0010" name=3D=
"bbr0010" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true" data-xocs-content-type=3D"r=
eference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0010"><span class=3D"anchor-text-contai=
ner"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[1]</span></span></a>, cognitive science <=
a class=3D"anchor anchor-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/sci=
ence/article/pii/S0021999118307125#br0020" name=3D"bbr0020" data-sd-ui-side=
-panel-opener=3D"true" data-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-conte=
nt-id=3D"br0020"><span class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"ancho=
r-text">[2]</span></span></a>, and genomics <a class=3D"anchor anchor-prima=
ry" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S002199911830=
7125#br0030" name=3D"bbr0030" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true" data-xo=
cs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0030"><span class=
=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[3]</span></span></a=
>. However, more often than not, in the course of analyzing complex physica=
l, biological or engineering systems, the cost of data acquisition is prohi=
bitive, and we are inevitably faced with the challenge of drawing conclusio=
ns and making decisions under partial information. In this <em>small data</=
em><span> regime, the vast majority of state-of-the-art <a href=3D"https://=
www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/machine-learning-technique" class=
=3D"topic-link">machine learning techniques</a> (e.g., deep/convolutional/r=
ecurrent neural networks) are lacking robustness and fail to provide any gu=
arantees of convergence.</span></div><div class=3D"u-margin-s-bottom" id=3D=
"pr0050"><span>At first sight, the task of training a <a href=3D"https://ww=
w.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/deep-learning" class=3D"topic-link">=
deep learning algorithm</a><span> to accurately identify a nonlinear map fr=
om a few =E2=80=93 potentially very high-dimensional =E2=80=93 input and ou=
tput data pairs seems at best naive. Coming to our rescue, for many cases p=
ertaining to the modeling of physical and biological systems, there exists =
a vast amount of prior knowledge that is currently not being utilized in mo=
dern machine learning practice. Let it be the principled physical laws that=
 govern the time-dependent dynamics of a system, or some empirically valida=
ted rules or other domain expertise, this prior information can act as a <a=
 href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/regularization" c=
lass=3D"topic-link">regularization</a><span> agent that constrains the spac=
e of <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/admissible=
-solution" class=3D"topic-link">admissible solutions</a> to a manageable si=
ze (e.g., in incompressible </span></span></span><a href=3D"https://www.sci=
encedirect.com/topics/engineering/fluid-dynamics" class=3D"topic-link">flui=
d dynamics</a> problems by discarding any non realistic flow solutions that=
 violate the conservation of mass principle). In return, encoding such stru=
ctured information into a learning algorithm results in amplifying the info=
rmation content of the data that the algorithm sees, enabling it to quickly=
 steer itself towards the right solution and generalize well even when only=
 a few training examples are available.</div><div class=3D"u-margin-s-botto=
m" id=3D"pr0060">The first glimpses of promise for exploiting structured pr=
ior information to construct data-efficient and physics-informed learning m=
achines have already been showcased in the recent studies of <a class=3D"an=
chor anchor-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/=
pii/S0021999118307125#br0040" name=3D"bbr0040" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=
=3D"true" data-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br00=
40"><span class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[4]</=
span></span></a>, <a class=3D"anchor anchor-primary" href=3D"https://www.sc=
iencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0021999118307125#br0050" name=3D"bbr00=
50" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true" data-xocs-content-type=3D"referen=
ce" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0050"><span class=3D"anchor-text-container"><=
span class=3D"anchor-text">[5]</span></span></a>, <a class=3D"anchor anchor=
-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S002199=
9118307125#br0060" name=3D"bbr0060" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true" d=
ata-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0060"><span c=
lass=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[6]</span></span=
></a><span>. There, the authors employed <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedire=
ct.com/topics/physics-and-astronomy/gaussian-distribution" class=3D"topic-l=
ink">Gaussian</a> process regression </span><a class=3D"anchor anchor-prima=
ry" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S002199911830=
7125#br0070" name=3D"bbr0070" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true" data-xo=
cs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0070"><span class=
=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[7]</span></span></a=
><span><span> to devise functional representations that are tailored to a g=
iven <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/linear-ope=
rator" class=3D"topic-link">linear operator</a><span>, and were able to acc=
urately infer solutions and provide uncertainty estimates for several proto=
type problems in mathematical <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topi=
cs/physics-and-astronomy/physics" class=3D"topic-link">physics</a>. Extensi=
ons to </span></span><a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engine=
ering/nonlinear-problem" class=3D"topic-link">nonlinear problems</a> were p=
roposed in subsequent studies by Raissi et al. </span><a class=3D"anchor an=
chor-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S00=
21999118307125#br0080" name=3D"bbr0080" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"tru=
e" data-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0080"><sp=
an class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[8]</span></=
span></a>, <a class=3D"anchor anchor-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedi=
rect.com/science/article/pii/S0021999118307125#br0090" name=3D"bbr0090" dat=
a-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true" data-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" dat=
a-xocs-content-id=3D"br0090"><span class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span cl=
ass=3D"anchor-text">[9]</span></span></a><span><span> in the context of bot=
h inference and <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/physics-and=
-astronomy/system-identification" class=3D"topic-link">systems identificati=
on</a>. Despite the flexibility and mathematical elegance of </span><a href=
=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/gaussian-process" clas=
s=3D"topic-link">Gaussian processes</a><span> in encoding prior information=
, the treatment of <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathemat=
ics/nonlinear-problem" class=3D"topic-link">nonlinear problems</a> introduc=
es two important limitations. First, in </span></span><a class=3D"anchor an=
chor-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S00=
21999118307125#br0080" name=3D"bbr0080" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"tru=
e" data-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0080"><sp=
an class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[8]</span></=
span></a>, <a class=3D"anchor anchor-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedi=
rect.com/science/article/pii/S0021999118307125#br0090" name=3D"bbr0090" dat=
a-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true" data-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" dat=
a-xocs-content-id=3D"br0090"><span class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span cl=
ass=3D"anchor-text">[9]</span></span></a><span> the authors had to locally =
linearize any <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/n=
onlinear-term" class=3D"topic-link">nonlinear terms</a><span> in time, thus=
 limiting the applicability of the proposed methods to discrete-time domain=
s and compromising the accuracy of their predictions in strongly nonlinear =
regimes. Secondly, the <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/math=
ematics/bayesian" class=3D"topic-link">Bayesian</a> nature of Gaussian proc=
ess regression requires certain prior assumptions that may limit the repres=
entation capacity of the model and give rise to robustness/brittleness issu=
es, especially for nonlinear problems </span></span><a class=3D"anchor anch=
or-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0021=
999118307125#br0100" name=3D"bbr0100" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true"=
 data-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0100"><span=
 class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[10]</span></s=
pan></a>.</div></section><section id=3D"se0020"><h2 id=3D"st0050" class=3D"=
u-h4 u-margin-l-top u-margin-xs-bottom">2. Problem setup</h2><div class=3D"=
u-margin-s-bottom" id=3D"pr0070"><span>In this work we take a different app=
roach by employing <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/chemical=
-engineering/deep-neural-network" class=3D"topic-link">deep neural networks=
</a><span> and leverage their well known capability as universal function <=
a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/approximators" c=
lass=3D"topic-link">approximators</a> </span></span><a class=3D"anchor anch=
or-primary" href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0021=
999118307125#br0110" name=3D"bbr0110" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true"=
 data-xocs-content-type=3D"reference" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0110"><span=
 class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">[11]</span></s=
pan></a><span>. In this setting, we can directly tackle <a href=3D"https://=
www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/nonlinear-problem" class=3D"topic-=
link">nonlinear problems</a><span> without the need for committing to any p=
rior assumptions, linearization, or local time-stepping. We exploit recent =
developments in <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics=
/automatic-differentiation" class=3D"topic-link">automatic differentiation<=
/a> </span></span><a class=3D"anchor anchor-primary" href=3D"https://www.sc=
iencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0021999118307125#br0120" name=3D"bbr01=
20" data-sd-ui-side-panel-opener=3D"true" data-xocs-content-type=3D"referen=
ce" data-xocs-content-id=3D"br0120"><span class=3D"anchor-text-container"><=
span class=3D"anchor-text">[12]</span></span></a><span> =E2=80=93 one of th=
e most useful but perhaps under-utilized techniques in <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/natural-sciences-computing" class=
=3D"topic-link">scientific computing</a><span> =E2=80=93 to differentiate <=
a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/chemical-engineering/neural-=
network" class=3D"topic-link">neural networks</a> with respect to their inp=
ut coordinates and model parameters to obtain </span></span><em>physics-inf=
ormed neural networks</em><span><span>. Such neural networks are constraine=
d to respect any symmetries, invariances, or conservation principles origin=
ating from the physical laws that govern the <a href=3D"https://www.science=
direct.com/topics/mathematics/observed-data" class=3D"topic-link">observed =
data</a>, as modeled by general time-dependent and </span><a href=3D"https:=
//www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/nonlinear-partial-differential-e=
quation" class=3D"topic-link">nonlinear partial differential equations</a><=
span>. This simple yet powerful construction allows us to tackle a wide ran=
ge of problems in computational science and introduces a potentially transf=
ormative technology leading to the development of new data-efficient and ph=
ysics-informed learning machines, new classes of numerical solvers for part=
ial differential equations, as well as new data-driven approaches for model=
 inversion and <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/physics-and-=
astronomy/system-identification" class=3D"topic-link">systems identificatio=
n</a>.</span></span></div><div class=3D"u-margin-s-bottom" id=3D"pr0080"><s=
pan>The general aim of this work is to set the foundations for a new paradi=
gm in modeling and computation that enriches <a href=3D"https://www.science=
direct.com/topics/engineering/deep-learning" class=3D"topic-link">deep lear=
ning</a><span> with the longstanding developments in <a href=3D"https://www=
.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/mathematical-physics" class=3D"topic-=
link">mathematical physics</a>. To this end, our manuscript is divided into=
 two parts that aim to present our developments in the context of two major=
 classes of problems: data-driven solution and data-driven discovery of par=
tial differential equations. All code and data-sets accompanying this manus=
cript are available on GitHub at </span></span><a class=3D"anchor anchor-pr=
imary" href=3D"https://github.com/maziarraissi/PINNs" target=3D"_blank"><sp=
an class=3D"anchor-text-container"><span class=3D"anchor-text">https://gith=
ub.com/maziarraissi/PINNs</span><svg focusable=3D"false" viewBox=3D"0 0 8 8=
" height=3D"20" aria-label=3D"Opens in new window" class=3D"icon icon-arrow=
-up-right-tiny arrow-external-link"><path d=3D"M1.12949 2.1072V1H7V6.85795H=
5.89111V2.90281L0.784057 8L0 7.21635L5.11902 2.1072H1.12949Z"></path></svg>=
</span></a><span>. Throughout this work we have been using relatively simpl=
e deep feed-forward <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/enginee=
ring/neural-network-architecture" class=3D"topic-link">neural networks arch=
itectures</a><span><span> with <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/top=
ics/engineering/hyperbolic-tangent" class=3D"topic-link">hyperbolic tangent=
</a><span><span> <a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineerin=
g/activation-function" class=3D"topic-link">activation functions</a> and no=
 additional </span><a href=3D"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineer=
ing/regularization" class=3D"topic-link">regularization</a> (e.g., L1/L2 pe=
nalties, dropout, etc.). Each </span></span><a href=3D"https://www.scienced=
irect.com/topics/mathematics/numerical-example" class=3D"topic-link">numeri=
cal example</a> in the manuscript is accompanied with a detailed discussion=
 about the neural network architecture we employed as well as details about=
 its training process (e.g. optimizer, learning rates, etc.). Finally, a co=
mprehensive series of systematic studies that aims to demonstrate the perfo=
rmance of the proposed methods is provided in Appendix </span></span><a cla=
